3j","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/wemk3j/what_are_you_doing_this_weekend"},{"short_id":"hg9mkc","created_at":"2026-06-19T07:29:04.000-05:00","title":"So You Want To Define a Well-Known URI","url":"https://mnot.net/blog/2026/well_known_uris","score":2,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"pushcx","user_is_author":false,"tags":["web"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/hg9mkc","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/hg9mkc/so_you_want_define_well_known_uri"},{"short_id":"sqiyga","created_at":"2026-06-19T07:19:16.000-05:00","title":"org-mindmap: Editable mindmaps for org-mode (krvkir)","url":"https://github.com/krvkir/org-mindmap","score":1,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"\u003cp\u003eSaw this posted on the emacs reddit.  It's insanely cool!  I've been thinking a lot lately about which 'knowledge' visualizations are useful and which are not so useful.  This one definitely falls into the former category, it's pretty elegant as a visualization for your org documents.  Check out the screenshot in the readme!  It's basically an explanation of what the package does using its own org-mindmap visualization (very cool idea, and very nice execution).  I see myself using this more-so than the PKM knowledge graphs, which tend to lose their utility for me after I've added enough nodes and edges.\u003c/p\u003e\n","description_plain":"Saw this posted on the emacs reddit.  It's insanely cool!  I've been thinking a lot lately about which 'knowledge' visualizations are useful and which are not so useful.  This one definitely falls into the former category, it's pretty elegant as a visualization for your org documents.  Check out the screenshot in the readme!  It's basically an explanation of what the package does using its own org-mindmap visualization (very cool idea, and very nice execution).  I see myself using this more-so than the PKM knowledge graphs, which tend to lose their utility for me after I've added enough nodes and edges.","submitter_user":"chiply","user_is_author":false,"tags":["emacs"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/sqiyga","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/sqiyga/org_mindmap_editable_mindmaps_for_org"},{"short_id":"ggp2ov","created_at":"2026-06-19T06:28:45.000-05:00","title":"Shutting Down Fornjot","url":"https://fornjot.app/blog/shutting-down-fornjot/","score":6,"flags":0,"comment_count":1,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"dzervas","user_is_author":false,"tags":["programming","rust"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/ggp2ov","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/ggp2ov/shutting_down_fornjot"},{"short_id":"u0nv8q","created_at":"2026-06-19T05:36:25.000-05:00","title":"DiffsHub","url":"https://diffshub.com/","score":6,"flags":0,"comment_count":2,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"quad","user_is_author":false,"tags":["vcs","vibecoding"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/u0nv8q","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/u0nv8q/diffshub"},{"short_id":"jtscci","created_at":"2026-06-19T04:20:18.000-05:00","title":"Rethinking modularity in Ruby applications","url":"https://noteflakes.com/articles/2026-06-18-syntropy-modules","score":2,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"noteflakes","user_is_author":true,"tags":["ruby","web"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/jtscci","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/jtscci/rethinking_modularity_ruby"},{"short_id":"cuh3be","created_at":"2026-06-19T03:41:53.000-05:00","title":"\"Mythos\" at Home, and It's Called AISLE","url":"https://stanislavfort.substack.com/p/mythos-at-home-and-its-called-aisle","score":2,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"daveliepmann","user_is_author":false,"tags":["security","vibecoding"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/cuh3be","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/cuh3be/mythos_at_home_it_s_called_aisle"},{"short_id":"heb0am","created_at":"2026-06-19T03:26:25.000-05: